On 7/17/07, magbard23 &lt;magbard23@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Hi all,
&gt;
&gt; I wondered if I&#39;m doing something wrong (most likely :) ) or whether
&gt; there is some design bug in the current 4.3.1 code:
&gt;
&gt; I have a bunch of testcases (JUnit4 with annotations) flying around but
&gt; I just want to run only a subset of those tests and decide (at runtime)
&gt; which ones I want to run (e.g. reading a config file etc and
&gt; instantiating the according Requests and passing them to eg the
&gt; JUnitCore)
&gt; More precisely, I wanted to run just one method at a time.
&gt;
&gt; From what I understand I need to create a Request that I can pass into
&gt; the JUnitCore in order to have it run.
&gt;
&gt; So I discovered that there is the option to create a Request that should
&gt; be filtered already by using Request.method() which says that it &quot;will
&gt; run a single test. This is done by filtering out all other tests.&quot;
&gt;
&gt; Now when I do that and pass that to the JUnitCore it still runs all
&gt; tests/methods in that class :( .. am I missing something?
&gt; (I suspect its related to the problem further down.. which in essence
&gt; would be that I cannot filter testcases that have a suite() method)
&gt;
&gt; Furthermore I tried to implement my own Filter which would just filter
&gt; out all unwanted methods using a Description.
&gt; Now there it seems that JUnit currently doesnt allow me to filter test
&gt; classes that contain the pre-v4 suite() methods
&gt; (unless I explicitly create the Request using
&gt; Request.classWithoutSuiteMethod())
&gt;
&gt; If I create the Request as ususal (Request.aClass()) the Runner that
&gt; gets created internally is a AllTests Runner which doesnt implement
&gt; Filterable.  As a result any filter.apply(Runner runner) calls have no
&gt; effect and the test is executed according to the suite() method.
&gt; So effectively I cannot filter test classes that have a suite() method.
&gt;
&gt; Is that a desired behavior?
&gt; Should this be documented?
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; This is some sample code to illustrate what I need to do to have a
&gt; Filter actually be applied to my Test class (i.e. with that code I get
&gt; just the testMethodName method invoked on the test class clazz ).
&gt;
&gt; // make a description with the methodname string
&gt; final Description d2 = Description.createTestDescription(clazz,
&gt; testMethodName);
&gt;
&gt; // anonymous inner class filtering out all tests where the description
&gt; // differs from this methodnames description
&gt; f = new Filter(){
&gt;      /** run only the test where the description matches */
&gt;      public boolean shouldRun(Description d) {
&gt;          return d2.equals(d);
&gt;      }
&gt;      public String describe() {
&gt;          return &quot;allows only methodname = &quot;+ testMethodName;
&gt;      }
&gt; };
&gt;
&gt; // weird hack: because most of our test cases have a suite method
&gt; // junit creates a AllTests runner which does not implement Filterable
&gt; // and hence the filter has no effect (and all methods are invoked)
&gt; // so as a fix we create a request for a class without suite() method
&gt; request = Request.classWithoutSuiteMethod(clazz);
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;   Thanks,
&gt;
&gt; Sebastian
